        <div class="item-info">
                <div class="slug-wrap">
                        <h3 class="slug"><a href="https://www.npr.org/sections/author-interviews/">Author Interviews</a></h3>
                </div>

            <h2 class="title"><a href="https://www.npr.org/2012/05/29/153705721/the-first-lady-cultivates-american-grown-gardening"  data-metrics='{"action":"Click Story Title","category":"Story List"}' >The First Lady Cultivates 'American Grown' Gardening</a></h2>
            
            
            <p class="teaser"><a href="https://www.npr.org/2012/05/29/153705721/the-first-lady-cultivates-american-grown-gardening"><time datetime="2012-05-29"><span class="date">May 29, 2012 &#149; </span></time>One of the first things Michelle Obama did as first lady was to dig up part of the beautifully manicured South Lawn of the White House and plant a vegetable garden. In her new book she says America has a long, proud history of gardening and it's time to reconnect with it.</a></p>

            

        </div>
